{"_id":"1ifiJNrDHGwCdH15","name":"Expose yourself to cost, retribution, or judgment","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p><strong>Cost </strong>means you pay a price, usually marking a condition yourself, to defend against the other PC.</p>\n<p><strong>Retribution </strong>means the other PC gets a chance to act against you without your interference.</p>\n<p><strong>Judgment </strong>means other people watching might judge you for your actions, leading them to shift your Labels (page 44) or otherwise act against you.</p>"}
{"_id":"7zKvMZuRBJgEQQ1X","name":"provoke a PC","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>If you&rsquo;re trying to provoke a PC, on a 7-9, you pick that either they must mark a condition if they don&rsquo;t do what you said you wanted them to do out of character, or you can add a Team to the pool if they do what you want.</p>\n<p>On a 10+, both are true. If they must mark a condition, they get to choose which condition they mark.</p>"}
{"_id":"9IRhbo1D95WWkHIm","name":"Taking something from them","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.zauAPAc1DlRxDV2A"}},"content":"<p>Taking something from them means you can take something physical or conceptual from the threat.</p>\n<p>You could, for instance, take the Doomray they&rsquo;re holding in their hands, knocking it out of their grip with one of your punches; or, you could take their footing, knocking them to the ground and giving you a chance to run; or, you could take their position in front of the controls for the Tachyon Cannon.</p>\n<p>This is your chance to use your attack to change your position and theirs.</p>"}
{"_id":"9osCMy3IFDmbxz1p","name":"What do you intend to do?","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>&ldquo;What do you intend to do?&rdquo; is about immediate plans, right here in the moment.</p>\n<p>It&rsquo;s a very action-focused question, giving you information on what you can expect to happen very soon.</p>"}
{"_id":"9vZ54YJYfCAYl07r","name":"How could I get your character to ___?","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>&ldquo;How could I get your character to ___?&rdquo; is one of your best ways to get other characters to do what you want in the game.</p>\n<p>You fill in the blank with whatever action you want them to take.</p>\n<p>They have to answer honestly, so whatever action or events they describe will genuinely get them to take the actions they&rsquo;ve promised.</p>\n<p>The answer might be &ldquo;You can&rsquo;t,&rdquo; because the question and what it&rsquo;s asking of them is so not in character, they just wouldn&rsquo;t do what you want them to.</p>"}
{"_id":"9zpUHx3k2eWrN8PP","name":"Keeping them safe","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>Keeping them safe means that you prevent the danger you acted against. If you&rsquo;re putting up an energy shield to stop someone from getting roasted, then on a hit, you do that&mdash;they&rsquo;re protected from the flame blast.</p>"}
{"_id":"BRPVCilpj0YBQUMB","name":"What here is in the greatest danger?","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>&ldquo;What here is in the greatest danger?&rdquo; is the inverse of the prior question.</p>\n<p>This tells you what needs protection the most, and potentially alerts you to the target or focus of a villain&rsquo;s attention&mdash;if they&rsquo;re after someone or something, chances are it&rsquo;ll be in the greatest danger.</p>"}
{"_id":"D08ezlMUg2Lr6fDQ","name":"Clearing a condition","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>Clearing a condition means you can immediately clear a condition you have marked, before you suffer any consequences for defending someone.</p>"}
{"_id":"EGIfCOlucOYBcCYd","name":"Taking Influence over someone you protect","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>Taking Influence over someone you protect means they care about how you&rsquo;ve helped them, and they&rsquo;re more inclined to listen to you moving forward.</p>\n<p>If you already had Influence over an NPC, there&rsquo;s little reason to take Influence over them again&mdash;you&rsquo;ll get +1 forward on your next move aimed at them, but that&rsquo;s it.</p>\n<p>However, taking Influence over a PC you already hold it over allows you to immediately shift their Labels.</p>\n<p>When you protect a whole bunch of people, you can either: name the specific person in the crowd that you want Influence over; let the GM tell you someone important in the crowd over whom you now have Influence; or take Influence over a whole group.</p>"}
{"_id":"ESEZsoL6PN6oaZtQ","name":"Unstable","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>Unstable is about unintended additional consequences, often dangerous to you or others. Unstable effects never take away from the core success of the roll&mdash;you still did whatever you intended to do.</p>\n<p>But they add an additional element that complicates the situation: collateral damage, unintended consequence, or worse.</p>\n<p>The GM might even make you roll to take a powerful blow as a result of an unstable effect.</p>"}
{"_id":"F3cuW3WEVJtK7Y5O","name":"they stumble","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>If the NPC stumbles, it means they were tripped up, caught on something, knocked off balance by your words.</p>\n<p>They&rsquo;re ill-prepared to deal with your next move; hence, you get +1 forward against them.</p>\n<p>Stumbling is essentially nonaction, allowing you to follow-up with a more straightforward move against them, at an advantage.</p>"}
{"_id":"FNN9ZWsRXDSiRehF","name":"Impress, surprise, or frighten the opposition","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>Impress, surprise, or frighten the opposition means you&rsquo;re affecting how the threat perceives you after you&rsquo;ve traded blows.</p>\n<p>Maybe you&rsquo;ve put on such a show of force, suddenly they view you with greater respect; or maybe you&rsquo;ve proved that you&rsquo;re a danger in a way they didn&rsquo;t see before, and now they try to get away from you.</p>\n<p>The GM picks which option (impress, surprise, or frighten) makes the most sense when you choose this option against an NPC threat.</p>\n<p>For NPCs or PCs, the GM might inflict a condition to represent the character&rsquo;s new perspective, if it fits the fiction.</p>"}
{"_id":"GEB6vrcTvusZYadZ","name":"Lashing out verbally","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>Lashing out verbally means you&rsquo;re thrown off your game, and you release the tension by snapping at someone you care about, usually another teammate.</p>\n<p>You have to immediately provoke them to take a foolhardy action, or you have to take advantage of your Influence over them to inflict a condition&mdash;any condition.</p>\n<p>Those are the only actions that satisfy &ldquo;lashing out verbally.&rdquo;</p>"}
{"_id":"GeOUHb2LpnugjLcz","name":"What here is the biggest threat?","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>&ldquo;What here is the biggest threat?&rdquo; helps you to prioritize dangers and threats in the area.</p>\n<p>You can clarify to the GM how you prioritize things yourself&mdash;so the GM knows whether you&rsquo;d think that the biggest threat is an enemy or something that endangers civilians, for instance.</p>\n<p>It&rsquo;s also useful even when you&rsquo;re not in an immediately dangerous situation to find out who&rsquo;s the most menacing in the room.</p>"}
{"_id":"Hkda71niRqJgM3qt","name":"Trading blows","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>Trading blows means both you and the threat get in some good hits on each other.</p>\n<p>That can lead to changes in the fiction&mdash;getting punched by a giant monster probably leaves you nice and bruised, unless you&rsquo;re utterly invulnerable.</p>\n<p>Beyond the fiction, though, this most often means inflicting conditions, or triggering the move take a powerful blow.</p>"}
{"_id":"ILWQgj7GpdBv5FdA","name":"Who here is most vulnerable to me?","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>&ldquo;Who here is most vulnerable to me?&rdquo; is about your own abilities and whom they can best affect.</p>\n<p>The obvious answers focus on who&rsquo;s most vulnerable to your particular skills and abilities, but it can also take into account who&rsquo;s most vulnerable to your words, if someone&lsquo;s susceptible to the things you could say.</p>"}
{"_id":"KKPqh0XnlFbDpFAC","name":"You must remove yourself from the situation","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>You must remove yourself from the situation means you&rsquo;re out. You&rsquo;re knocked from the scene somehow.</p>\n<p>You get ultimate say in how exactly you&rsquo;re removed, but you should follow the fiction.</p>\n<p>If you just got punched in the face, you probably got knocked out.</p>\n<p>You&rsquo;ll come back next scene, but all your conditions will still be marked.</p>"}
{"_id":"KVorPk12DYMhnvgV","name":"Giving ground","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>Giving ground means you retreat, or hold back, or otherwise leave an opening for your opposition.</p>\n<p>The GM decides what it is, but usually it means your opposition can make some move they otherwise would&rsquo;ve been blocked from, without you being able to stop them.</p>"}
{"_id":"LLEXc6xhG78oVdYY","name":"What are you really planning?","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>&ldquo;What are you really planning?&rdquo; is about long term plans.</p>\n<p>It&rsquo;s about overarching goals and intent, not immediate intent.</p>\n<p>The answer could be &ldquo;Nothing,&rdquo; but most characters have some kind of overarching goal and plan that they can use to answer the question.</p>"}
{"_id":"ON16SC2HxbsTMx3t","name":"they overreact","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>If the NPC overreacts, it means you take Influence over them, and they take an exaggerated or extreme reaction in response to what you say, something that shows you&rsquo;ve really gotten to them.</p>\n<p>This isn&rsquo;t the same as erring&mdash;their overreaction might not give you any kind of opportunity or even a chance to react. Instead, it shows how much your words actually affected them.</p>\n<p>They might start firing their eyebeams at you in response to your taunting.</p>\n<p>They might lose their composure and start insulting you directly.</p>"}
{"_id":"TGsXFDv7tstLtKqE","name":"they err","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>If the NPC errs, it means they take action without planning or thinking and it leaves them vulnerable or creates an opportunity that you wouldn&rsquo;t have otherwise had.</p>\n<p>They might take a swing at you, leaving them open for you to simply knock them out with one punch.</p>\n<p>They might accidentally let information slip in an attempt to tell you off.</p>"}
{"_id":"TaV1RQnD4a0yJZDM","name":"Resisting or avoiding their blows","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.nUAfyo1BTbLny9XQ"}},"content":"<p>Resisting or avoiding their blows means you aren&rsquo;t affected by the trading of blows&mdash;you either get out of the way of the threat&rsquo;s strikes or you can just shrug them off, depending on what makes sense for your character and the threat.</p>\n<p>This ensures that you come through unscathed, but it doesn&rsquo;t get you anything else&mdash;it means all you&rsquo;ve done is struck the threat and most likely inflicted a condition on them.</p>"}
{"_id":"UaE1Ne1Da5aIDnNR","name":"How could I gain Influence over you?","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>&ldquo;How could I gain Influence over you?&rdquo; is one of the most straightforward ways of getting Influence on someone.</p>\n<p>If you already have Influence over them, the question won&rsquo;t tell you anything; if you don&rsquo;t, this tells you what you need to do to ensure that your words and opinions matter to them.</p>\n<p>If you do whatever they tell you to do, they should grant you Influence immediately after.</p>"}
{"_id":"Ywir3A7ghlywXICY","name":"Creating an opportunity for your allies","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.9Nv4x6pbDP2UQ4xa"}},"content":"<p>Creating an opportunity for your allies means you&rsquo;re giving your teammates (or other allies) an opening to act or to gain some kind of advantage.</p>\n<p>Maybe you hold the villain off to the side, so your teammate has a shot at reaching the Neutrino Bomb.</p>\n<p>Maybe you smash the villain straight through the air towards your teammate, giving them a chance to land a follow-up strike.</p>\n<p>Either way, this option sets up team maneuvers.</p>\n<p>Sometimes, you choose this to change the actual situation so your teammate has a chance to do something they couldn&rsquo;t otherwise do.</p>\n<p>Other times, you&rsquo;re just giving your teammate a boost.</p>\n<p>If it&rsquo;s the former, then choosing this option gives your teammate that chance.</p>\n<p>If it&rsquo;s the latter, though, then you should add a Team to the pool. (For more on Team and the Team Pool, see page 48.) The GM tells you which it is.</p>"}
{"_id":"bi3ybJTbGf51hrFA","name":"What do you want me to do?","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>&ldquo;What do you want me to do?&rdquo; puts a focus on the other person&rsquo;s vision and ideas for you and how they want you to act.</p>\n<p>You can usually offer to act how they want in exchange for getting something from them.</p>"}
{"_id":"fQGbtM3ds2EI3qYS","name":"What here can I use to _____?","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>&ldquo;What here can I use to _____?&rdquo; lets you fill in the blank when you ask the question.</p>\n<p>This is a great question for finding useful tools and pieces of your surroundings that will help you accomplish some purpose.</p>\n<p>Want to trap Vanquish?</p>\n<p>Ask &ldquo;What here can I use to trap Vanquish?&rdquo; and the GM will tell you.</p>\n<p>The answer might be &ldquo;nothing.&rdquo;</p>"}
{"_id":"gxBpPu8qOnTba08K","name":"You lose control of yourself or your powers in a terrible way","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>You lose control of yourself or your powers in a terrible way means the GM gets to tell you how your powers go haywire, cause collateral damage, make the world around you unstable, and all kinds of other bad stuff.</p>\n<p>Losing control of yourself means that you might say or do something awful.</p>\n<p>The GM chooses which you do, and what exactly that looks like.</p>"}
{"_id":"iuNHVscvQTU12BlT","name":"Struggling past the pain","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>Struggling past the pain means you mark two conditions of your choice.</p>\n<p>You hurt, but you keep going.</p>"}
{"_id":"kQAC51RVPCip8K4n","name":"Temporary","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>Temporary is pretty self-explanatory&mdash;it puts a time pressure on the effect, and it could be anything from, &ldquo;You&rsquo;ve wrapped the villain in a metal cage, but he&rsquo;s gonna break out soon, you&rsquo;ve only bought yourself a bit of time,&rdquo; to &ldquo;You&rsquo;ve managed to lift up the debris of the collapsed building with your gravity powers, but you can only hold it up for a bit longer.&rdquo;</p>"}
{"_id":"pooi4bbuZX5yqrG4","name":"How could we best end this quickly?","permission":{"default":0,"PIYJckcNzA7ukurN":3},"flags":{},"content":"<p>&ldquo;How could we best end this quickly?&rdquo; outlines a course of action to stop a dangerous or bad situation as quickly as possible.</p>\n<p>This could be how best to take down an enemy quickly, but it might tell you that the best way to end things quickly is to flee.</p>\n<p>It might also tell you that all you have to do is apologize to bring a bad situation to a close.</p>"}
